edu.stanford.nlp.ling
Class MapLabel

java.lang.Object
  edu.stanford.nlp.ling.AbstractMapLabel
      edu.stanford.nlp.ling.MapLabel
All Implemented Interfaces:
HasCategory, HasContext, HasTag, HasWord, Label, Serializable
public class MapLabel
extends AbstractMapLabel

An AbstractMapLabel implementation which uses Object equality and hashcode. This is useful when one wants to refer to token instances, such as to particular nodes in a tree.

As standardly used, a key of a MapLabel is always a String, but the value can be an arbitrary object.

Author:
Bill MacCartney, Teg Grenager

MapLabel

public MapLabel(Label label)
Create a new MapLabel with the value of another Label as its value.

If the argument label is a MapLabel, the new label is identical to the argument label (but does not share storage). If the argument is a MapLabel, it just copies the map, but doesn't make copies of the map's contents.

If the argument label implements HasWord and/or HasTag, such as a CategoryWordTag, the category, word, and tag are stored in the map of the new label under the map keys CATEGORY_KEY, WORD_KEY, and TAG_KEY, respectively.

Parameters:
label - the other label

toString

public String toString(String format)
Returns a formatted string representing this label. The desired format is passed in as a String. Currently supported formats include:
  • "value": just prints the value
  • "{map}": prints the complete map
  • "value{map}": prints the value followed by the contained map (less the map entry containing key CATEGORY_KEY)
  • "value-index": extracts a value and an integer index from the contained map using keys INDEX_KEY, respectively, and prints them with a hyphen in between
  • "value-index{map}": a combination of the above; the index is displayed first and then not shown in the map that is displayed
  • "word": Just the value of HEAD_WORD_KEY in the map

Map is printed in alphabetical order of keys.
